07189nam a22007935i 9780226517568DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20202018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017039550  a9780226517568  a(DE-B1597)568256  a(OCoLC)1198930401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aLC191b.E4248 2018 4aLC191b.E4248 2018 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a306.43097322300aEducation in a New Society :bRenewing the Sociology of Education /ced. by Scott Davies, Jal Mehta. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b9 halftones, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword / A Much-Needed Project -- tONE / Education in a New Society: Renewing the Sociology of Education -- tPART ONE Theoretical Perspectives -- tTWO Social Theory and the Coming Schooled Society -- tTHREE / The Deepening Interpenetration of Education in Modern Life -- tFOUR An Institutional Geography of Knowledge Exchange: Producers, Exports, Imports, Trade Routes, and Metacognitive Metropoles -- tFIVE Professional Education in the University Context: Toward an Inhabited Institutional View of Socialization -- tPART TWO Substantive Contributions -- tSIX Talking Pigs? Lessons from Elite Schooling -- tSEVEN What’s Up with Assessment? -- tEIGHT College and University Campuses as Sites for Political Formation: A Cultural-Organizational Approach -- tNINE Digital Badges and Higher Education in a New Society: A Bernsteinian Analysis -- tTEN Research Universities and the Global Battle for the Brains -- tPART THREE Old Themes, New Perspectives -- tELEVEN The Expansion of the “School Form” and Deepening Inequality -- tTWELVE / Reopening the Black Box of Educational Disadvantage: Why We Need New Answers to Old Questions -- tTHIRTEEN / Schools as Great Distractors: Why Socioeconomic-Based Achievement Gaps Persist -- tFOURTEEN / Race and White Supremacy in the Sociology of Education: Shifting the Intellectual Gaze -- tFIFTEEN / Race, Ethnicity, and Cultural Processes in Education: New Approaches for New Times -- tSIXTEEN / Claim No Easy Victories: Some Notes toward a Fearless Sociology of Education -- tEPILOGUE / What Next for the Sociology of Education? -- tINDEX OF AUTHORS -- tINDEX OF SUBJECTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades, sociology of education has been dominated by quantitative analyses of race, class, and gender gaps in educational achievement. And while there’s no question that such work is important, it leaves a lot of other fruitful areas of inquiry unstudied. This book takes that problem seriously, considering the way the field has developed since the 1960s and arguing powerfully for its renewal. The sociology of education, the contributors show, largely works with themes, concepts, and theories that were generated decades ago, even as both the actual world of education and the discipline of sociology have changed considerably. The moment has come, they argue, to break free of the past and begin asking new questions and developing new programs of empirical study. Both rallying cry and road map, Education in a New Society will galvanize the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducational sociologyzUnited States. 0aEducational sociology. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aeducation, educational, learning, college, university, classroom, teacher, student, social studies, society, sociology, sociologist, academic, scholarly, research, professor, leadership, policy, race, racism, class, classism, gender, gaps, 1960s, contemporary, 20th century, themes, theories, theoretical, empirical, study, united states, school, schooling, modern life, metacog